      {
        "content": "Mike Markkula, a former Intel executive, is identified by Jobs as the third key figure in the creation of Apple, following Jobs and Wozniak. Markkula came aboard during the design phase of the Apple II, a period when the founders had developed much higher ambitions for the company than during the Apple I era.\n\nMike Markkula, a former Intel executive, is identified by Jobs as the third key figure in the creation of Apple, following Jobs and Wozniak. Markkula came aboard during the design phase of the Apple II, a period when the founders had developed much higher ambitions for the company than during the Apple I era. Steve Jobs and Mike Markkula 'hit it off very well' during their initial interactions. Markkula agreed to invest in Apple after a few weeks of consideration, marking a pivotal moment in the company's formation and providing the necessary capital for the Apple II's production.\n\nMike Markkula, a former Intel executive, is identified by Jobs as the third key figure in the creation of Apple, following Jobs and Wozniak. Markkula came aboard during the design phase of the Apple II, a period when the founders had developed much higher ambitions for the company than during the Apple I era. Steve Jobs and Mike Markkula 'hit it off very well' during their initial interactions. Steve Jobs successfully convinced Mike Markkula to join Apple not just as an investor, but as an 'equal partner,' contributing both capital and his personal involvement. This partnership solidified the core team of three—Jobs, Wozniak, and Markkula—who collectively drove the final stages of the Apple II's development and launch. Markkula agreed to invest in Apple after a few weeks of consideration, marking a pivotal moment in the company's formation and providing the necessary capital for the Apple II's production.",
        "title": "Mike Markkula as the Third Key Figure",
