        "content": "[995.319s - 1124.000s]\nwant your money we want you so we convinced Mike to actually throw in with us as an equal partner and so Mike put in some money and Mike put in himself and the three of us went off and we took this design that was virtually done with the Apple 2 and toed it up and announced it um a few months later at the West Coast computer Fair what was that like it was great uh we got the the best I mean this is the West Coast computer fair was small at that time but to us it was very large and so uh we had this fantastic booth there uh we had a projection television showing the Apple 2 and showing its Graphics which today look very crude but at that time we're by far the most advanced graphics on a personal computer and I think you know my recollection is we stole the show and a lot of dealers and Distributors started lining up and we were off and running how old were you 21 21 yeah you're 21 you're a big success you know you you have no you just sort of done it by the seat of your pants you don't have any particular training in this how do you how do you learn to run a company um you know throughout the years in business I found something which was I'd always ask why you do things and the answers you invariably get are oh that's just the way it's done nobody knows why they do what they do nobody thinks about things very deeply in business that's what I found I'll give you an example um when we were building our Apple ones in the garage we knew exactly what they cost uh when we got into a factory in the Apple 2 days",
        "title": "Steve Jobs - The Lost Interview - Part 9/36",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-27T22:20:16.000Z",
        "source": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRZAJY23xio"
      },
      {
        "content": "Steve Jobs critiqued the traditional accounting practice of 'standard cost,' where costs are estimated and adjusted via variance at the end of a quarter. He realized this method was a workaround for inadequate information systems and poor controls, forcing companies to 'guess' costs and fix them later rather than knowing them in real-time.",
        "title": "Jobs' Critique of Standard Cost Accounting",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-27T22:20:45.000Z",
        "source": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRZAJY23xio"
      },
      {
        "content": "The implementation of the automated factory for the Macintosh allowed Apple to eliminate antiquated accounting concepts like standard cost variances. This technological advancement enabled the company to know the exact cost of production 'to the second,' providing real-time financial precision that was previously impossible.",
        "title": "Macintosh Factory and Real-Time Cost Tracking",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-27T22:20:46.000Z",
        "source": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRZAJY23xio"
      },
      {
        "content": "Jobs described many business practices as 'folklore,' meaning they are performed simply because they were done that way in the past. He argued that by asking questions and thinking critically, one can demystify these practices and learn business quickly, asserting that business is 'not rocket science.'",
        "title": "Business Practices as Folklore",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-27T22:20:47.000Z",
        "source": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRZAJY23xio"
      },
      {
        "content": "During the design of the blue box, Jobs and Wozniak used computers to write custom programs that handled the 'dog work' of calculating master frequencies and sub-divisors. These programs helped determine frequency errors and tolerances, demonstrating an early use of computing for complex engineering calculations.",
        "title": "Computer-Assisted Design of the Blue Box",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-27T22:20:48.000Z",
        "source": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRZAJY23xio"
      },
      {
        "content": "Jobs emphasized that the root cause of relying on standard cost accounting was insufficient information systems. He connected the ability to discard these 'antiquated concepts' directly to the sophistication of their manufacturing technology, highlighting the interplay between operational tech and financial clarity.",
        "title": "Information Systems as the Foundation of Cost Accuracy",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-27T22:20:48.000Z",
        "source": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRZAJY23xio"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) observe that Jobs' dismissal of standard accounting as 'folklore' reinforces his broader philosophy of first-principles thinking. By refusing to accept 'that's just how it's done,' he identified a systemic inefficiency (lack of real-time data) that he later solved through vertical integration and automation.",
        "title": "Agent Observation on Jobs' First-Principles Approach to Accounting",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-27T22:20:49.000Z",
        "source": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRZAJY23xio"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) note the significance of Jobs using computers to design the blue box, which predates Apple's formation. This illustrates that his view of computers as tools for amplifying human intellect and solving complex problems was formed through personal experience with engineering tasks, not just commercial ambition.",
