      },
      {
        "content": "Steve Jobs views computer programming as a 'mirror of your thought process' and a tool for learning how to think, rather than just a practical skill. He argues that the greatest value of programming is its ability to structure cognitive processes, making it a valuable educational discipline for everyone.",
        "title": "Jobs on Programming as a Mirror for Thought",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-27T22:21:16.000Z",
        "source": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRZAJY23xio"
      },
      {
        "content": "Jobs advocates that everyone in the country should learn to program a computer language because it teaches a specific mode of thinking. He compares this to law school, noting that while few should become lawyers, the process of legal education teaches valuable analytical skills, just as programming teaches a different but equally valuable way of thinking.",
        "title": "Jobs' Analogy Between Programming and Law School",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-27T22:21:16.000Z",
        "source": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRZAJY23xio"
      },
      {
