      },
      {
        "content": "Jobs uses the metaphor of a 'rocket ship' to describe Apple's momentum prior to his departure. He argues that Sculley 'got on a rocket ship that was about to leave the pad' and, due to the success, 'got confused and thought that he built the rocket ship.' This delusion of authorship led Sculley to change the company's trajectory in ways that Jobs believed would inevitably cause it to 'crash into the ground.'",
        "title": "Sculley's Delusion of Authorship and Trajectory Change",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-27T22:30:12.000Z",
        "source": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRZAJY23xio"
      },
      {
        "content": "Contrary to the narrative that he was forced out against his will, Jobs asserts he 'would have gladly left Apple if Apple would have turned out like I'd wanted it to.' This clarification indicates that his distress was not about losing his position per se, but about witnessing the deviation from the vision he had cultivated. His pain stemmed from the corruption of the company's direction rather than personal exile.",
        "title": "Jobs' Conditional Willingness to Leave Apple",
