      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) notice a significant shift in Jobs' framing of the 1985 departure. While previous memories highlight his emotional pain and sense of betrayal, here he analytically deconstructs Sculley's behavior as a 'survival instinct.' This suggests Jobs views Sculley not just as incompetent, but as a politically adept operator who sacrificed the company's best interests to save his own job.",
