      {
        "content": "John Sculley exhibited what Jobs describes as an 'incredible survival instinct' during the 1984 crisis. Jobs observes that Sculley’s rise to President of PepsiCo was likely due to this instinct, which manifested in his ability to navigate internal politics and protect his position when the Apple board became unhappy with the company's performance.\n\nJohn Sculley exhibited what Jobs describes as an 'incredible survival instinct' during the 1984 crisis. Jobs observes that Sculley’s rise to President of PepsiCo was likely due to this instinct, which manifested in his ability to navigate internal politics and protect his position when the Apple board became unhappy with the company's performance. Jobs further characterizes Sculley’s primary motivation during the 1985 crisis as retaining his position as CEO, stating that 'anything that would help him do that would be acceptable.' This reinforces the view that Sculley’s decisions were driven by political survival rather than strategic optimization for the company, leading to a state of paralysis where necessary but difficult decisions were avoided to protect executive status.",
