      {
        "content": "Jobs identifies the most significant consequence of his departure not as his personal loss, but as the systematic destruction of Apple's core values over the subsequent years. He argues that while his exile was tragic, the erosion of the company's cultural and ethical foundations was the more important and damaging outcome, implying that the loss of identity was more detrimental than the loss of specific leadership figures.",
