      },
      {
        "content": "Steve Jobs proposed a compromise to remain at Apple in 1985: starting a research division with a budget of 'a few million bucks a year' to hire top talent and work on the 'next great thing.' He volunteered for this role to continue contributing to innovation without the burden of running the entire company, but this proposal was rejected, with leadership stating there was 'no opportunity' for such an initiative.\n\nSteve Jobs proposed a compromise to remain at Apple in 1985: starting a research division with a budget of 'a few million bucks a year' to hire top talent and work on the 'next great thing.' He volunteered for this role to continue contributing to innovation without the burden of running the entire company, but this proposal was rejected, with leadership stating there was 'no opportunity' for such an initiative. This rejection is interpreted as a missed opportunity for Apple to maintain its innovation pipeline during a transitional period. By refusing to allow Jobs to focus on 'the next great thing,' Apple not only lost his immediate contributions but also potentially delayed the development of future technologies, forcing Jobs to channel that energy into NeXT instead.",
