      },
      {
        "content": "Steve Jobs identifies three critical strategic imperatives for Apple in early 1985: establishing the Macintosh as the future of the company, reigning back expenses in the Apple II division, and spending heavily on Macintosh development. He argues that these shifts required much stronger leadership to unite the various factions created by the divisional structure, a unifying force that was absent due to the leadership vacuum at the top.\n\nSteve Jobs identifies three critical strategic imperatives for Apple in early 1985: establishing the Macintosh as the future of the company, reigning back expenses in the Apple II division, and spending heavily on Macintosh development. He argues that these shifts required much stronger leadership to unite the various factions created by the divisional structure, a unifying force that was absent due to the leadership vacuum at the top. During this period of paralysis, Jobs admitted he was not yet capable of running the whole company at age 30, but noted that CEO John Sculley was also lacking in experience. Sculley's primary vision was to remain CEO, viewing any action that secured his position as acceptable. When Jobs proposed an alternative—creating a research division with a few million dollars to hire top talent for the 'next great thing'—he was rejected and told there was no job for him, describing the outcome as being sent to 'Siberia.' Jobs viewed this period as tragic, noting that Apple's values were systematically destroyed in the following years.",
