      {
        "content": "Jobs attributes the greatness of the Macintosh to the diverse backgrounds of its creators, specifically noting that the team included 'musicians and poets.' This highlights his belief that technological excellence requires a liberal arts perspective, where those with artistic and humanistic sensibilities contribute to engineering and product design.\n\nJobs attributes the greatness of the Macintosh to the diverse backgrounds of its creators, specifically noting that the team included 'musicians and poets,' as well as top-tier computer scientists who were also artists, zoologists, and historians. He notes that without computer science, these individuals would have been achieving amazing things in their respective fields, bringing a 'liberal arts attitude' to the technical effort. This highlights his belief that technological excellence requires a liberal arts perspective, where those with artistic, humanistic, and scientific sensibilities contribute to engineering and product design.\n\nJobs attributes the greatness of the Macintosh to the diverse backgrounds of its creators, specifically noting that the team included 'musicians and poets,' as well as top-tier computer scientists who were also artists, zoologists, and historians. He notes that without computer science, these individuals would have been achieving amazing things in their respective fields, bringing a 'liberal arts attitude' to the technical effort. This highlights his belief that technological excellence requires a liberal arts perspective, where those with artistic, humanistic, and scientific sensibilities contribute to engineering and product design.\n\nJobs emphasizes that the Macintosh team intentionally sought to 'pull in the best' insights from non-technical fields like history and zoology into computer science. He argues that this interdisciplinary approach is impossible to achieve if one remains 'very narrow' in their perspective, highlighting the necessity of broad cultural exposure for true innovation.",
